“I’m 100 years old, but I remember the 1st time I saw her so vividly. A panditji matched our kundlis, so my family & I went to see her. I still annoy her that I only went ahead because of my parents. But between us, she was so beautiful, I couldn’t stop staring. I didn’t think she’d say ‘yes’ to a man ten years older than her, but the elders talked, baat pakki hogayi & we were married. There was no honeymoon phase; we were thrust into a joint family with strict rules. With little money to ourselves, everyday was a struggle. My brother bought us clothes, because I didn’t have enough to even buy her a saree. But she never complained. I’d drive around South India delivering agarbattis for 3 weeks every month, but she never let me feel guilty. I trusted her so much that I only felt right about a decision if she approved it. So, even though everyone thought it was a reckless move, she stood by me when I left the family business to start my own. She gave me courage & said, ‘We’ll get through it together.’ I dreamt of giving her our own home. I clocked long hours at the office, while she ran the house. We didn’t have much, but she made me feel like the richest man in the world when she sat by my side after a long day. After 17 years of saving every penny, we made that dream a reality. We built a new life in this home. Every morning, I’d make the bed, while she made the softest dosas. In the evenings, she’d pick out flowers from our garden, & I’d peek through the newspaper to gaze at her. Carnatic music always filled the air at home & every Sunday, we had a date at a concert! After our daughters were married, we took our first trip abroad. I was scared of getting lost & insisted on sitting in the tour bus, but she said, ‘nothing will happen, let’s go’ & took me all around town! I’ve lived a century now, & I still need her advice on the smallest of things. My kids often tease me & ask, ‘Did your wife say ‘yes’ to this?’ & we both laugh! Last year, on our 71st anniversary, we renewed our vows because two kids, 4 grandkids and 2 great grandkids later, one lifetime is simply not enough to celebrate our love.”
